:"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1059206e9cdfa0201e2f13d43181c730?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":66,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/66/alexander-galkin","reputation":5247,"display_name":"Alexander Galkin"},"score":15,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"score":4,"post_id":770,"edited":false,"creation_date":1327355677,"comment_id":865,"body":"Note there is a slightly higher mortality rate for males, which tends to bring the ratio towards 50:50 at reproduction age."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1348920479,"creation_date":1327321143,"body":"<p><strong>The Fisher's principle is not applicable to the fetuses<\/strong> because it has been formulated for parental expenditure and basically states that the ratio of male to female parents (implying that both parties have reached the age of fertility) will tend to 1:1. <\/p>\n\n<p>There are several mechanisms that we can use and that are mentioned in the canonical paper by <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1677/JOE-07-0446\" rel=\"nofollow\">James (2007)<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>(a) there are equal numbers of X and Y chromosomes in mammalian sperms<br>\n  (b) X and Y stand equal chance of achieving conception<br>\n  (c)\n  therefore equal number of male and female zygotes are formed, and that<br>\n  (d) therefore any variation of sex ratio at birth is due to sex\n  selection between conception and birth.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>James brings much evidence that none of these conventional beliefs is true. Rather, they are dependent upon many factors: exposure to stress during pregnancy, glucose level etc. He reports that there is an excess of males at birth in almost all human populations, and the natural sex ratio at birth is usually between 1.02 and 1.08. However, the ratio may deviate significantly from this range for natural reasons. (I really recommend reading the paper I linked, it is available for free).<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/humrep/dep255\" rel=\"nofollow\">Branum <em>et al<\/em> (2009)<\/a> analyze birth statistics in the US taking into account many factors like ethnicity, gestational age and plurality and show that the ratio can increase even more with growing gestational age and has different values among different races.<\/p>\n\n<p>So, taking everything together, I can say thay <strong>YES, the chances for human fetuses to be male are indeed higher<\/strong>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":770,"question_id":768,"up_vote_count":15,"last_edit_date":1348920479},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"score":8,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/adb4704a0cb6b43c3a59eb46c637189b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":251,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/251/kasia","reputation":676,"display_name":"Kasia"},"score":0,"post_id":780,"edited":false,"creation_date":1329414398,"comment_id":1269,"body":"Could you provide some reference for the last paragraph, ie. that the ratio might be dependent on the weight of Y &amp; X chromosomes?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"score":0,"post_id":780,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/adb4704a0cb6b43c3a5