cy where oxyhemoglobin and hemoglobin have identical absorbance).<\/p>\n\n<p>As far as I know, there's no reason why a green LED wouldn't work. You would only be able to measure the PPG signal and not the oximetry data (unless you used two different LEDs and did some math). <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0305049197002307\" rel=\"nofollow\">Absorption curves<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":9806,"question_id":9805,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a0fed698d5c2a733cd47849022ca469c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4246,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4246/sliders-alpha","reputation":111,"display_name":"sliders_alpha"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1376676192,"creation_date":1376676192,"body":"<p>Found the difference in colors :<\/p>\n\n<p>Longer wavelenght penetrate deeper. <\/p>\n\n<p>because main artifacts are caused by changes in the blood volume at the measurement site. During movement, the changes in venous blood volume are larger than those in arterial one. While the penetration depth of light is dependent on its wavelength, and green\nlight do not penetrate as deeply as infrared light. Therefore, the green PPG would include less information from various non-pulsatile sources than the infrared PPG.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>I also looked up multi-spectral ppg and from what I read they all give you an exploitable PPG signal, it really depends from what you want to do.\nFor oximeter you need red and ifr light source. but if ou just want a pulse meter shorter wavelenght are better.<\/p>\n\n<p>Sources :<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://embc.embs.org/files/2013/3170_FI.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://embc.embs.org/files/2013/3170_FI.pdf<\/a>\n<a href=\"http://www.biofotonika.lu.lv/fileadmin/user_upload/lu_portal/projekti/biofotonika/Publikacijas/A3/Asare_8073_76_Praga.PDF\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.biofotonika.lu.lv/fileadmin/user_upload/lu_portal/projekti/biofotonika/Publikacijas/A3/Asare_8073_76_Praga.PDF<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":9808,"question_id":9805,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9805/what-is-the-best-color-for-a-ppg-signal-photoplethysmography","last_activity_date":1376676192,"creation_date":1376645329,"answer_count":2,"title":"What is the best color for a PPG signal (photoplethysmography)?","body":"<p>What is the best color for a PPG signal?\nRed, green, blue or infra-red?<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm asking because commercial oximeter sensors usually use a pair of red and infra-red LEDs. But recently, I've seen a lot of sensors using green LEDs.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks.<\/p>\n","question_id":9805,"tags":["human-biology","hematology"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1344,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1376657150},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":9807,"edited":false,"creation_date":1376712452,"comment_id":12885,"body":"there is a software called UNAfold (same website as mFold) which allows nucleic acid hybridization."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9807/visualizing-secondary-rna-structure-binding-to-target","last_activity_date":1376668511,"creation_date":1376668127,"answer_count":0,"title":"Visualizing secondary RNA structure binding to target","body":"<p>I am designing synthetic ribozymes, and need to see the secondary structure that arises from its flanking arms binding to a tar