3.full\" rel=\"nofollow\">This study on blind people<\/a> will show you that the light entering the eyes is the (main at least) regulator of melatonin rhythms. They took blind people, 19 of whom could perceive light and 30 who could not, and showed that 14 of 19 light perceivers had normal melatonin rhythms while 23 of the light-blind people had abnormal or unclassifiable rhythms.<\/p>\n","answer_id":9491,"question_id":9490,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1375108411}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9490/why-do-you-need-you-room-dark-for-melatonin-release","last_activity_date":1375625818,"creation_date":1375091387,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do you need you room dark for melatonin release?","body":"<p>There is a light pollution movement that says lighting at night obstructs melatonin production. They say: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>What makes you fall asleep are changes in the level of the hormone\n  melatonin circulating in your body. During the day, light stimulates a\n  part of the brain. This brain part (known as the suprachiasmatic\n  nucleus) tells the pineal gland to decrease the melatonin level when\n  it is light out and to increase it when it is dark. The brighter the\n  light, the bigger the decrease and the darker the dark, the bigger the\n  increase of melatonin. By making your days lighter and your nights\n  darker, you can improve both the quality of your sleep and the amount\n  of time it takes you to fall asleep.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>and recommend all kind of protection against the light, <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Dark Nights: Make your nights as dark as possible. Draw the curtains,\n  close the shades and keep the lights off. Try a sleep mask if you\n  can\u2019t get eliminate enough light. The darker your night, the quicker\n  you will fall asleep.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Do I sense the light by the whole skin surface or only open eyes? If you sense by eyes, which are closed during the sleep, then what is the problem?<\/p>\n\n<p>In other words, the question is: is the sleep mask sufficient for melatonin secretion or you need to cover the skin?<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>update<\/strong> What if I close only one eye? I tend to do this when the blinding sun shines. Does such light eject melatonin?<\/p>\n","question_id":9490,"tags":["human-biology","sleep","melatonin"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":4224,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1375625818},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8d1f59d2b9f599b976e94b484c2e6e24?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1413,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1413/winerd","reputation":288,"display_name":"winerd","accept_rate":47},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZORFM.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3370,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3370/mikedugan","reputation":455,"display_name":"mikedugan"},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8d1f59d2b9f599b976e94b484c2e6e24?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1413,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1413/winerd","reputation":288,"display_name":"winerd","accept_rate":47},"score":0,"post_id":9619,"edited":false,"creation_date":1375636371,"comment_id":12656,"body":"So are you saying that antacids raise the pH of the lower gut, the acidic environment in turn inhibits the breakdown of lactulose into acidic metabolites? I guess that then less water is retained in the bowel than would be without an antacid, making lactulose less efficient against constipation."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZORFM.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3370,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3370/mikedugan","reputation":455,"display_name":"mikedugan"},"score":0,"post_id":9619,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8d1f59d2b9f599b976e94b484c2e6e24?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1413,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1413/winerd","reputation":288,"display_name":"winerd","accept_rate":47},"edited":false,"creation_date":1375636881,"comment_id":12657,"body":"The antacids don&#39;t necessarily inhibit the breakdown of lactulose, but they counteract the effect that would be caused by a more acidic environment in the gut. Acidity = increased peristaltic (bowel) movement. So the gross amount of acidic product from the lactulose might still be the same, but it is being neutralized to some extent by the alkaline products of the antacids."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8d1f59d2b9f599b976e94b484c2e6e24?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1413,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1413/winerd","reputation":288,"display_name":"winerd","accept_rate":47},"score":0,"post_id":9619,"edited":false,"creation_date":1375638034,"comment_id":12658,"body":"Many thanks for your answer. In the main text you wrote \u201cantacids \u2026 raise the pH of the lower gut\u201d, in your comment \u201calkaline products of the antacids\u201d. Isn&#39;t that a contradiction? Do I misunderstand something?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZORFM.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3370,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3370/mikedugan","reputation":455,"display_name":"mikedugan"},"score":1,"post_id":9619,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8d1f59d2b9f599b976e94b484c2e6e24?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1413,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1413/winerd","reputation":288,"display_name":"winerd","accept_rate":47},"edited":false,"creation_date":1375639072,"comment_id":12659,"body":"pH &lt;7 is acidic, pH &gt; 7 is basic/alkalinic, so the antacids (calcium carbonate, etc) would raise the pH, making it more alkalinic and less acidic, hence the &quot;antacid&quot;"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1375622323,"creation_date":1375622323,"body":"<p>Other laxatives can exacerbate the effects of lactulose, leading to diarrhea, and could eventually lead to dehydration and general GI issues.<\/p>\n\n<p>Neomycin and antacids in general raise the pH of the gut, making it more basic, and reducing the peristaltic movements. Lactulose, meanwhile, is broken down to primarily lactic acid (if I recall) in the gut, and creates a more acidic environment. The acidic environment increases peristaltic movement in the bowel, and in turn the patient eliminates waste.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you are on concomitant antacids or other drugs that raise the pH of the lower gut, you are reducing the effects of lactulose, and in a worse case scenario, making the constipation worse.<\/p>\n","answer_id":9619,"question_id":8807,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/8807/why-do-antacids-have-a-special-importance-when-taking-lactulose","last_activity_date":1375622323,"creation_date":1371322064,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do antacids have a special importance when taking lactulose?","body":"<p>\u201c<em>Before taking lactulose, tell your doctor and pharmacist what prescription and nonprescription medications you are taking, especially <strong>antacids<\/strong>, antibiotics including neomycin (Mycifradin), and other laxatives.<\/em>\u201d (Quote from <a href=\"http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginfo/meds/a682338.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>)<\/p>\n\n<p>Why do antacids have a special importance when taking lactulose?<\/p>\n","question_id":8807,"tags":["pharmacology","digestive-system"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":9619,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":826,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1371568576},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","